.TH CPPINDENT 1 "March 2026" "cppindent 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
cppindent \- reformat C/C++ preprocessor directive indentation
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B cppindent
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] [\fISOURCES...\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBcppindent\fR is a small formatting tool that normalizes the indentation of
C and C++ preprocessor directives. It does not reformat normal C code; only
lines whose first non\-whitespace character is '\fB#\fR' are considered.
.PP
The primary goal is to normalize indentation of nested macro blocks. Two
indentation styles are supported:
.IP \[bu]
indent after '\fB#\fR' (default),
.IP \[bu]
indent before '\fB#\fR'.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-a
Indent after '\fB#\fR' (default). Indentation characters are inserted between
the '\fB#\fR' and the directive keyword.
.TP
.B \-b
Indent before '\fB#\fR'. Indentation characters are placed before the
directive marker; the '\fB#\fR' itself remains flush to the directive text.
.TP
.B \-i
Edit files in place. For each source file, \fBcppindent\fR writes formatted
output to a temporary file and atomically replaces the original on success.
.TP
.B \-w\fINUM\fR
Use spaces for indentation with width \fINUM\fR per nesting depth (default
4). This option disables tab indentation even if \fB\-t\fR was given earlier.
.TP
.B \-t
Use literal tab characters for indentation. The number of tabs written is
equal to the current nesting depth. This option overrides any previous
\fB\-w\fR setting.
.SH INDENTATION MODEL
The nesting depth is derived only from conditional preprocessing directives.
.PP
The following increase depth (after the current line is formatted):
.PP
.RS
\fB#if\fR, \fB#ifdef\fR, \fB#ifndef\fR
.RE
.PP
The following decrease depth (before the current line is formatted):
.PP
.RS
\fB#endif\fR
.RE
.PP
The following keep the same depth:
.PP
.RS
\fB#else\fR, \fB#elif\fR
.RE
.PP
Other directives such as \fB#define\fR, \fBundef\fR, \fBinclude\fR, \fBpragma\fR,
\fBerror\fR, \fBwarning\fR and \fBline\fR do not affect nesting depth.
.SH INPUT AND OUTPUT
If no source files are specified, \fBcppindent\fR reads from standard input
and writes to standard output.
.PP
When one or more \fISOURCES\fR are provided without \fB\-i\fR, each file is
read and the formatted result is written to standard output in sequence.
.PP
With \fB\-i\fR, each file is rewritten in place using a temporary file and
an atomic rename. File permissions are preserved where possible.
.SH DIAGNOSTICS
If \fB#endif\fR is encountered at depth zero, a warning about an unmatched
\fB#endif\fR is printed to standard error and depth is clamped to zero.
.PP
If the end of a file is reached with a positive depth, a warning about a
missing \fB#endif\fR is printed.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Command line usage error.
.TP
.B 2
File processing error.
.SH AUTHOR
Written for the cppindent project.

